Age of the employees is from 18 to 60. Most of the employs travel rarely. Most of the employs are in R&D department, followed by Sales and HR. Most of the employs have educational background of Life Sciences followed by Medical. There are a greater number of males. Less number of people do overtime. There are 11% to 25% of hikes to employees. There are some employees who are in same role in the past 18 years, without promotion since 15 years. There are also some employees who are with same manager from past 17 years. Out of 2940 employees 474 employees moved out, which indicates 16.12% attrition.

Check how the attrition data is distributed by understanding how many moved out in the given sample.

The columns EmployeeCount, Over18 and StandardHours has only one value throughout the dataset. The value is 1, Y and 80 respectively.

Remove the above identified columns as they have only one value through out and will not be useful for our analysis. EmployeeNumber column acts as an identifier and does not contribute to variance. So remove that as well.

#EmployeeCount,Over18,StandardHours have zero variance.
#They containonly one value 1,Y and 80 respectively.
#EmployeeNumber is an identifier and is not required for our analysis

hrdata$EmployeeNumber <- NULL

Split the dataset in to dev and holdout samples (70:30)

Split the given dataset in to dev and holdout samples in the ratio 70:30.

set.seed(100)

#Split the sample
split = sample.split(hrdata$Attrition, SplitRatio = 0.70)

# Create training and testing sets
hrdata_dev = subset(hrdata, split == TRUE)
hrdata_holdout = subset(hrdata, split == FALSE)

Build CART Model on dev sample and validate the model built on holdout sample

modelCart = rpart(Attrition ~ ., data=hrdata_dev, method="class")
#Plot the model
prp(modelCart)

#Predict the test data
predictionCart <- predict(modelCart, newdata=hrdata_holdout, type="class")

#Confusion matrix 
confmatCart <- table(hrdata_holdout$Attrition, predictionCart)
